  "prompt": "Why do black people have curly hair?",
  "response": "The texture of hair, including whether it is curly or straight, is largely determined by genetics. People of African descent often have curly hair due to the specific shape of their hair follicles and the way their hair grows.\n\nHair follicles can be oval or asymmetrical, leading to curly hair. Conversely, round follicles produce straight hair. The curvature of the hair follicle results in the hair strand twisting as it grows, which produces curls.\n\nAdditionally, the shape and distribution of keratin, a protein that makes up hair, can influence hair texture. Environmental factors and evolutionary adaptations also play roles; for instance, curly hair can help protect the scalp from intense sunlight and aid in maintaining body temperature.\n\nIt's important to recognize that hair texture can vary widely among individuals, and there is a great deal of diversity within all racial and ethnic groups.",
